WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.160
[Amit Varma]: Where were you when India won the 1983 World Cup? I was 9 years old then, assembled with

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:17.020
[Amit Varma]: my family at the home of my uncle, Babul Mama, in Hauskas in New Delhi. I didn't follow

00:00:17.020 --> 00:00:21.720
[Amit Varma]: cricket in those days, but I also got caught up in the drama, how could you not, when all

00:00:21.720 --> 00:00:26.040
[Amit Varma]: the adults around you were going mad. And the madness reached its peak when Michael

00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:31.320
[Amit Varma]: Holding was out to Mohinder Amanath and celebrations erupted in the living room. I was even then

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:35.520
[Amit Varma]: the voice of reason and I tried to calm everyone down, saying that hey, the match isn't over,

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:40.320
[Amit Varma]: there's still one West Indies batsman left. As I said, I didn't follow cricket then. Of

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:45.040
[Amit Varma]: course, that changed as I grew up and cricket became a big part of my life and indeed that

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:50.440
[Amit Varma]: of so many of my fellow Indians. We can remember where we were when big sporting moments happened,

00:00:50.440 --> 00:00:55.040
[Amit Varma]: when Miyandad hit that six of my fellow Chandigarhian Chetan Sharma, when Ravi Shastri won that

00:00:55.040 --> 00:01:01.120
[Amit Varma]: Audi, when Jadeja, Ajay Jadeja, not Ravindra, blasted Waqar Yunus in the 1996 World Cup,

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:05.800
[Amit Varma]: when Lakshman and Ravid did that thing they did, when Kumle bowled with a broken jaw,

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:09.960
[Amit Varma]: when Dhoni gave the ball to Joginder Sharma, when Virat Kohli lifted Sachin Tendulkar on

00:01:09.960 --> 00:01:15.520
[Amit Varma]: his shoulders at the Wankhede Stadium in 2011. And it's not just cricket, we remember moments

00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:20.240
[Amit Varma]: in other sports as well and the other heroes we celebrated, from Abhinav Bindra to Leander

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:25.640
[Amit Varma]: Pace to Sena Nehwal to my favourite Vishy Anand. Sport was part of the emotional journey

00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:30.520
[Amit Varma]: we made getting here. And it also reflected the journey our nation made, with all its

00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:35.800
[Amit Varma]: flaws and aspirations and assertions. It's a hell of a story. And when it's told by a

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:43.840
[Amit Varma]: hell of a writer, it can reach a place within us that nothing else can.

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:49.280
[Unknown]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:55.960
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:55.960 --> 00:02:00.480
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen. My guest today is Sharda Ogre, who should need no introduction,

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:04.800
[Amit Varma]: but hey, I might as well do it anyway. Over three decades, Sharda has written about practically

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:11.000
[Amit Varma]: every sport in the country and built a body of work that is inspiring, moving and enlightening.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.200
[Amit Varma]: She started at midday, went on to the Hindu in India today, and then spent a few years

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:20.360
[Amit Varma]: at ESPN Crickinfo, though after my time, so I can't quite call her a colleague. I've loved

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:24.280
[Amit Varma]: her writing ever since I first read her, and I was delighted to get her on the show for

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:29.000
[Amit Varma]: a conversation about sports journalism and the state of Indian sport. Sharda combines

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:35.100
[Amit Varma]: two qualities that are hard to find in most writers. She's both clear eyed and empathetic.

00:02:35.100 --> 00:02:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And I love the way she can find the human stories in sport, while also shedding light

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:44.280
[Amit Varma]: on the bigger picture, the larger context. I won't say more about her because I try to

00:02:44.280 --> 00:02:48.920
[Amit Varma]: avoid hyperbole, but I'll simply say that she is my favourite sports writer in the whole

00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:53.560
[Amit Varma]: world. Now, despite being a cricket journalist myself for a few years, I don't actually remember

00:02:53.560 --> 00:02:58.820
[Amit Varma]: hanging out with her at any point or even having a conversation. So this was much awaited,

00:02:58.820 --> 00:03:03.180
[Amit Varma]: and it will remain much awaited for you for another 90 seconds or so. Because before we

00:03:03.180 --> 00:03:11.280
[Amit Varma]: get to the conversation, we will take a quick commercial break.

